  The GNU Affero General Public License is a free, copyleft license for
software and other kinds of works, specifically designed to ensure
cooperation with the community in the case of network server software.

  The licenses for most software and other practical works are designed
to take away your freedom to share and change the works.  By contrast,
the GNU Affero General Public License is intended to guarantee your
freedom to share and change all versions of a program--to make sure it
remains free software for all its users.

  When we speak of free software, we are referring to freedom, not
price.  Our General Public Licenses are designed to make sure that you
have the freedom to distribute copies of free software (and charge for
them if you wish), that you receive source code or can get it if you
want it, that you can change the software and use pieces of it in new
free programs, and that you are aware of all these things.

  Developers that use our General Public Licenses protect your rights
with two steps: (1) assert copyright on the software, and (2) offer
you this License which gives you legal permission to copy, distribute
and/or modify it.

  A secondary benefit of defending all users' freedom is that
improvements made in alternate versions of the program, if they
receive widespread use, become available for the public to benefit
from.  Many developers of free software are heartened and encouraged
by the implied cooperation that results from this practice.  However,
in the case of software used on network servers, this benefit is lost
if the changes are only used locally.  For a program used in a service,
its freedom is of less importance than the freedom of users of the
service running on their own machines.

  The GNU Affero General Public License aims to protect the freedom of
users to modify the program and run private modified versions, while
also ensuring that these modifications are available to them and others
connected through a network server.

  This license applies to any software or other work which contains a
notice placed by the copyright holder saying it can be distributed
under the terms of this License. Most software is distributed under
this license. If the program is a service, the users of the service
should be offered a way to obtain a copy of the source code, which
is provided under this License.

  When a program invokes functions from a library, whether in source or
binary form, the library itself does not impose any restrictions on the
use of the program (other than that which results from running the
program).  This is because the main libraries of free operating systems
are themselves free software.  However, many people have written
libraries under the GPL that are technically derived works of your
program.  If you link such a library with your program, you may have
the option of making the library proprietary.  If you want to avoid
this, you must use the LGPL (the lesser GNU general public license).
If you think a library is proprietary, you should use the original GPL.

